VALUES
(44, 19, 5, 46, 1, 13, 15, 'baptized in the name of the Lord Jesus', 'Baptism in the Name of Jesus', 'Both passages emphasize the act of baptism and its significance. Acts 19:5 highlights baptism in the name of the Lord Jesus, while 1 Corinthians 1:13-15 questions the authority of baptism in the names of others, reinforcing the importance of being baptized in Christ''s name.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 19, 6, 44, 2, 4, 4, 'spake with tongues', 'Connection of Holy Spirit Manifestation', 'Both passages emphasize the filling of the Holy Ghost and the speaking with tongues. This connection highlights a consistent theme of the Holy Spirit empowering believers to speak in diverse languages.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 19, 6, 44, 6, 6, 6, NULL, 'Connection of Laying on Hands', 'Both passages emphasize the act of laying hands, which signifies the impartation of spiritual gifts or authority. In Acts 19:6, this act results in the Holy Ghost coming upon the recipients, while in Acts 6:6, it is part of the commissioning process for the chosen individuals.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 19, 6, 41, 16, 17, 17, NULL, 'Connection of Speaking in Tongues', 'Both passages emphasize the act of speaking with new tongues as a sign of belief and the presence of the Holy Spirit. Acts 19:6 illustrates the fulfillment of this promise as Paul lays hands on believers, resulting in them speaking with tongues.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 19, 6, 54, 5, 22, 22, 'laid his hands upon them', 'Connection of Laying on Hands', 'This connection highlights the act of laying hands as a significant practice in both passages. In Acts, laying hands results in the Holy Spirit''s presence, while in 1 Timothy, it warns against hastily laying hands on others, emphasizing the importance of discernment.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 19, 6, 46, 14, 1, 25, 'spake with tongues, and prophesied', 'Connection of Spiritual Gifts', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of prophesying over speaking in tongues for the edification of the church. Acts 19:6 describes the coming of the Holy Spirit, which enables speaking in tongues, while 1 Corinthians 14:1-25 discusses the greater value of prophesying for building up the community.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 19, 6, 55, 1, 6, 6, NULL, 'Connection of Spiritual Gifts', 'This connection highlights the theme of the Holy Spirit''s empowerment through the laying on of hands. Both passages emphasize the act of imparting spiritual gifts, as seen in the reception of the Holy Ghost and the stirring up of God''s gift.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 19, 6, 46, 12, 8, 11, 'spake with tongues, and prophesied', 'Connection of Spiritual Gifts', 'This connection highlights the manifestation of the Holy Spirit in both passages. Acts 19:6 describes the Holy Ghost empowering believers to speak in tongues and prophesy, while 1 Corinthians 12:8-11 lists various gifts of the Spirit, including tongues and prophecy.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 19, 8, 44, 1, 3, 3, 'things concerning the kingdom of God', 'Connection on the Kingdom of God', 'Both passages emphasize speaking about the kingdom of God. Acts 1:3 mentions Jesus discussing this theme for forty days, while Acts 19:8 shows Paul doing so for three months.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 19, 8, 44, 28, 23, 23, 'the kingdom of God', 'Connection of Kingdom of God', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of ''the kingdom of God'' and the act of persuading others about it. In each instance, the speaker engages in discussion and testimony regarding this central theme, highlighting its importance in their ministry.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 19, 8, 44, 9, 20, 22, 'spake boldly for the space of three months', 'Preaching in the Synagogue', 'Both passages emphasize the act of preaching in the synagogues. In Acts 19:8, the focus is on disputing and persuading about the kingdom of God, while in Acts 9:20-22, Saul preaches Christ as the Son of God.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 19, 8, 65, 1, 3, 3, 'spake boldly', 'Contending for the Faith', 'This connection highlights the theme of boldly advocating for the faith. Both passages emphasize the importance of persuasion and contention in relation to the kingdom of God and the faith delivered to the saints.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 19, 8, 44, 13, 14, 14, 'synagogue', 'Synagogue Engagement in Acts', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of the synagogue as a setting for preaching and teaching. In Acts 19:8, the focus is on bold discourse about the kingdom of God, while Acts 13:14 highlights the act of entering the synagogue to engage with the community.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 19, 9, 44, 19, 23, 23, 'that way', 'Stir About That Way', 'This connection highlights the growing opposition to ''that way'' as seen in both passages. In Acts 19:9, the hardened individuals speak evil of ''that way,'' leading to a significant disturbance mentioned in Acts 19:23.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 19, 9, 44, 9, 2, 2, NULL, 'Connection of ''this way''', 'Both passages emphasize the phrase ''this way,'' referring to the early followers of Jesus. Acts 19:9 shows a separation from those who opposed ''this way,'' while Acts 9:2 illustrates the pursuit of those who belonged to it.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 19, 9, 61, 2, 12, 12, 'spake evil of that way', 'Connection of Speaking Evil', 'Both passages emphasize the act of speaking evil against what is not understood. In Acts, individuals spoke evil of ''that way,'' while in 2 Peter, it describes those who speak evil of things they do not comprehend.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 19, 9, 45, 9, 18, 18, 'hardened', 'Connection of Hardening and Mercy', 'This connection highlights the theme of hardening present in both passages. Acts 19:9 describes individuals who were ''hardened'' and rejected the message, while Romans 9:18 speaks of God hardening whom He wills.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 19, 9, 45, 11, 7, 7, 'hardened, and believed not', 'Blinded Hearts and Disbelief', 'This connection highlights the theme of hardened hearts and disbelief in both passages. Acts 19:9 describes individuals who were hardened and did not believe, while Romans 11:7 speaks of Israel being blinded, indicating a similar spiritual condition.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 19, 9, 54, 6, 5, 5, 'disputing daily in the school', 'Disputing and Withdrawal Theme', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of withdrawing from those who engage in corrupt disputations. Acts 19:9 describes Paul separating from those who spoke evil, while 1 Timothy 6:5 advises withdrawal from men of corrupt minds.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 19, 9, 58, 3, 13, 13, 'hardened', 'Hardened Hearts and Exhortation', 'This connection highlights the theme of being ''hardened'' in both passages. Acts 19:9 describes individuals who were hardened and did not believe, while Hebrews 3:13 warns against being hardened through sin. Both emphasize the importance of community support to prevent spiritual hardening.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 19, 10, 44, 20, 31, 31, 'by the space of two years', 'Duration of Ministry Emphasis', 'Both passages emphasize the duration of ministry efforts, with Acts 19:10 noting two years of preaching and Acts 20:31 referencing three years of warning. This connection highlights the commitment to spreading the word of the Lord over an extended period.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 19, 10, 55, 1, 15, 15, NULL, 'Rejection in Asia', 'This connection highlights the geographical reference to Asia in both passages. Acts 19:10 states that all in Asia heard the word, while 2 Timothy 1:15 notes that those in Asia have turned away from Paul.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 19, 10, 44, 16, 6, 6, 'heard the word of the Lord Jesus', 'Preaching in Asia Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the spread of the word in Asia. Acts 19:10 shows that all in Asia heard the word, while Acts 16:6 indicates a restriction on preaching in Asia, highlighting a significant shift in the mission''s progress.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 19, 10, 45, 1, 16, 16, 'both Jews and Greeks', 'Connection of Gospel to All', 'Both passages emphasize the inclusivity of the gospel, reaching both Jews and Greeks. Acts 19:10 notes that all in Asia heard the word, while Romans 1:16 states the gospel is for everyone who believes, highlighting its universal message.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 19, 10, 45, 10, 12, 12, 'both Jews and Greeks', 'Unity of Jews and Greeks', 'This connection highlights the inclusivity of the Gospel message, as both passages emphasize that the word of the Lord Jesus reached all people, regardless of their ethnic background. The mention of ''both Jews and Greeks'' in Acts parallels the assertion in Romans that there is ''no difference between the Jew and the Greek.''', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 19, 10, 46, 1, 22, 24, 'both Jews and Greeks', 'Connection Between Evangelism and Response', 'This connection highlights the spread of the gospel in Asia, where both Jews and Greeks heard the word. Both passages emphasize the differing responses to Christ, with Jews seeking signs and Greeks seeking wisdom, yet all are called to recognize Christ''s power and wisdom.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 19, 10, 48, 3, 28, 28, 'all they which dwelt in Asia heard', 'Unity in Christ Across Cultures', 'This connection highlights the inclusivity of the Gospel message. Both passages emphasize that all people, regardless of cultural or social distinctions, are united in Christ Jesus.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 19, 11, 41, 16, 17, 20, 'special miracles by the hands of Paul', 'Miracles and Signs Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the miraculous signs that accompany believers. Acts 19:11 describes Paul performing special miracles, while Mark 16:17-20 outlines the signs that will follow those who believe, including healing and casting out devils.', 'theme', 0.412, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 19, 11, 44, 5, 12, 12, 'by the hands of', 'Miracles by Apostolic Hands', 'Both passages emphasize the miraculous works performed by the hands of apostles, highlighting the divine authority and power given to them. This connection illustrates the continuity of miraculous signs in the early church.', 'theme', 0.412, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 19, 11, 45, 15, 18, 19, 'special miracles by the hands of Paul', 'Miracles and Signs in Ministry', 'This connection highlights the theme of divine power in Paul''s ministry. Both passages emphasize the role of ''mighty signs and wonders'' as evidence of God''s work through Paul.', 'theme', 0.40499999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 19, 11, 58, 2, 4, 4, 'special miracles', 'Miracles and Divine Witness', 'Both passages emphasize the role of God in performing miracles through His chosen instruments. Acts 19:11 highlights special miracles by Paul, while Hebrews 2:4 mentions God bearing witness with signs and wonders.', 'theme', 0.398, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 19, 11, 44, 8, 13, 13, NULL, 'Miracles and Belief Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the role of miracles in fostering belief. In Acts 19:11, special miracles by Paul demonstrate God''s power, while Acts 8:13 shows Simon''s belief stemming from witnessing miracles and signs.', 'theme', 0.377, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 19, 11, 48, 3, 5, 5, NULL, 'Miracles and Faith Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of miracles being associated with faith. Both passages emphasize that miracles are not achieved through the law but through the Spirit and faith.', 'theme', 0.37, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 19, 11, 43, 14, 12, 12, 'special miracles', 'Miraculous Works of Believers', 'Both passages emphasize the ability to perform miracles. Acts 19:11 describes Paul performing special miracles, while John 14:12 states that believers will do greater works. This connection highlights the continuity of miraculous works through faith.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 19, 12, 44, 5, 15, 15, 'the sick', 'Healing through physical objects', 'Both passages emphasize the miraculous healing associated with physical objects. In Acts 19:12, handkerchiefs are used to heal the sick, while in Acts 5:15, the shadow of Peter is believed to bring healing to those laid in the streets.', 'theme', 0.398, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 19, 12, 12, 13, 20, 21, 'the diseases departed from them', 'Healing through contact', 'Both passages emphasize the power of physical contact with holy objects or remains to bring healing and restoration. In Acts, handkerchiefs from Paul heal the sick, while in 2 Kings, touching Elisha''s bones revives a man.', 'theme', 0.391, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 19, 12, 41, 16, 17, 17, NULL, 'Signs of Healing and Deliverance', 'Both passages emphasize the power of believers to heal and cast out evil spirits. Acts 19:12 illustrates the physical manifestation of this power through handkerchiefs, while Mark 16:17 outlines the signs that accompany those who believe, including casting out devils.', 'theme', 0.37, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 19, 12, 12, 4, 29, 31, 'the diseases departed from them', 'Healing through physical objects', 'This connection highlights the use of physical items, such as handkerchiefs and staffs, in the healing process. Both passages emphasize the belief in the power of these objects to bring about healing and the departure of evil spirits or death.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 19, 13, 40, 12, 27, 27, 'by Jesus whom Paul preacheth', 'Exorcism and Authority Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of authority in exorcism. In Acts, the exorcists invoke Jesus'' name, while in Matthew, Jesus questions the source of authority for casting out demons.', 'theme', 0.37, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 19, 13, 41, 9, 38, 38, 'by Jesus whom Paul preacheth', 'Exorcism in Jesus'' Name', 'This connection highlights the use of Jesus'' name in exorcisms. Both passages emphasize the authority of Jesus'' name in casting out evil spirits.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 19, 13, 42, 11, 19, 19, 'by Jesus whom Paul preacheth', 'Exorcism and Authority in Jesus'' Name', 'This connection highlights the theme of authority in casting out evil spirits. In Acts, the exorcists invoke Jesus'' name, while in Luke, Jesus questions the source of authority for casting out devils.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 19, 13, 44, 8, 18, 19, 'Jesus whom Paul preacheth', 'Use of Jesus'' Name in Exorcism', 'This connection highlights the misuse of spiritual authority. Both passages emphasize the desire to invoke power associated with Jesus, whether for exorcism or for the Holy Spirit.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 19, 13, 41, 5, 7, 7, 'We adjure you by Jesus', 'Invocation of Jesus'' Name', 'Both passages emphasize the act of invoking Jesus'' name in the context of confronting evil spirits. In Acts, the exorcists use the name of Jesus whom Paul preaches, while in Mark, the demon addresses Jesus directly, invoking God''s authority. This connection highlights the power attributed to Jesus'' name in spiritual confrontations.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 19, 13, 42, 9, 49, 49, 'by Jesus whom Paul preacheth', 'Exorcism in Jesus'' Name', 'This connection highlights the use of Jesus'' name in exorcisms. Both passages emphasize the authority of Jesus'' name in casting out evil spirits.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 19, 13, 11, 22, 16, 16, NULL, 'Use of the Name of the Lord', 'This connection highlights the invocation of the name of the Lord in both passages. In Acts, the exorcists use the name of Jesus, while in 1 Kings, the king seeks truth in the name of the Lord.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 19, 15, 44, 16, 17, 18, 'Jesus I know, and Paul I know', 'Authority of Jesus and Paul', 'This connection highlights the recognition of Jesus and Paul by the evil spirit in Acts 19:15, paralleling the authority demonstrated by Paul in casting out the spirit in Acts 16:17-18. Both passages emphasize the power of the name of Jesus in spiritual matters.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 19, 15, 41, 1, 34, 34, 'who are ye?', 'Recognition of Jesus and Paul', 'Both passages emphasize the recognition of spiritual authority. In Acts, the evil spirit acknowledges Jesus and Paul, while in Mark, the devils know Jesus, indicating a shared theme of recognition by evil spirits.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 19, 15, 41, 5, 9, 13, 'Jesus I know', 'Recognition of Authority', 'This connection highlights the recognition of Jesus'' authority by evil spirits in both passages. In Acts, the evil spirit acknowledges Jesus and Paul, while in Mark, the unclean spirits identify themselves as Legion, indicating their awareness of Jesus'' power.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 19, 15, 42, 4, 33, 35, 'Jesus I know', 'Recognition of Jesus'' Authority', 'Both passages emphasize the recognition of Jesus'' identity and authority by evil spirits. In Acts, the evil spirit acknowledges Jesus and Paul, while in Luke, the unclean devil recognizes Jesus as ''the Holy One of God.'' This connection highlights the theme of spiritual recognition of divine power.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 19, 15, 40, 8, 29, 31, 'Jesus I know', 'Recognition of Jesus'' Authority', 'Both passages emphasize the recognition of Jesus'' authority by evil spirits. In Acts, the spirit acknowledges Jesus and Paul, while in Matthew, the demons recognize Jesus as the Son of God and express fear of his power.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 19, 15, 42, 8, 28, 32, 'Jesus I know', 'Recognition of Jesus'' Authority', 'This connection highlights the recognition of Jesus'' authority over evil spirits. In both passages, the spirits acknowledge Jesus'' power, with the evil spirit in Acts recognizing Jesus and Paul, while the demon in Luke directly addresses Jesus as the Son of God.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 19, 15, 1, 3, 1, 5, 'Jesus I know, and Paul I know', 'Knowledge of Authority', 'This connection highlights the theme of recognition of authority. In Acts, the evil spirit acknowledges Jesus and Paul, paralleling the serpent''s assertion of knowledge in Genesis about God''s command.', 'theme', 0.321, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 19, 16, 41, 5, 3, 4, 'overcame them, and prevailed against them', 'Connection of Demonic Power', 'Both passages emphasize the overwhelming strength of evil spirits. In Acts, the evil spirit prevails against the men, while in Mark, the man with the unclean spirit cannot be bound by chains, showcasing the formidable nature of demonic influence.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 19, 16, 42, 8, 29, 29, 'the evil spirit was leaped on them', 'Connection of Evil Spirits', 'Both passages emphasize the power of evil spirits over individuals. In Acts, the evil spirit prevails against the men, while in Luke, the unclean spirit drives the man into the wilderness, showcasing the destructive influence of these spirits.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 19, 16, 41, 5, 15, 15, NULL, 'Possession and Transformation', 'Both passages emphasize the state of individuals possessed by evil spirits. In Acts, the man overcomes the exorcists, while in Mark, the possessed man is transformed, sitting and clothed, indicating a restoration of dignity.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 19, 16, 42, 8, 35, 35, NULL, 'Contrast of Evil Spirits', 'This connection highlights the transformation of individuals affected by evil spirits. In Acts, the man with the evil spirit overcomes others, while in Luke, the man freed from demons is found ''clothed, and in his right mind.''', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 19, 17, 53, 1, 12, 12, 'the name of the Lord Jesus', 'Magnifying the Name of Jesus', 'This connection highlights the emphasis on the name of the Lord Jesus being magnified in Acts and glorified in 2 Thessalonians. Both passages reflect the importance of the name of Jesus in the lives of believers.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 19, 17, 44, 5, 5, 5, NULL, 'Fear and Magnification of Jesus', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of fear that arises in response to divine acts. In Acts 19:17, fear leads to the magnification of the name of the Lord Jesus, while in Acts 5:5, fear comes upon those who witness a serious event involving Ananias.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 19, 17, 44, 5, 11, 11, 'fear fell on them all', 'Fear and Magnification of Jesus', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of fear that arises in response to divine acts. In Acts 19:17, fear leads to the magnification of the name of the Lord Jesus, while Acts 5:11 describes fear coming upon the church and those who heard about miraculous events.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 19, 17, 50, 1, 20, 20, 'the name of the Lord Jesus was magnified', 'Magnification of Christ''s Name', 'This connection highlights the theme of magnifying the name of Jesus. Both passages emphasize the act of making Christ known and glorified, whether through miraculous events or personal testimony in life and death.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 19, 17, 50, 2, 9, 11, 'the name of the Lord Jesus', 'Exaltation of Jesus'' Name', 'This connection highlights the magnification of Jesus'' name in both passages. Acts emphasizes the fear and reverence that arose in Ephesus, while Philippians proclaims that Jesus'' name is exalted above all, leading to universal acknowledgment of His lordship.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 19, 17, 53, 3, 1, 1, 'the name of the Lord Jesus was magnified', 'Magnifying the Word of the Lord', 'Both passages emphasize the glorification of the Lord. Acts 19:17 mentions the name of the Lord Jesus being magnified, while 2 Thessalonians 3:1 speaks of the word of the Lord being glorified.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 19, 17, 3, 10, 3, 3, 'the name of the Lord Jesus was magnified', 'Sanctification and Glorification', 'Both passages emphasize the glorification of the Lord. In Acts, the name of the Lord Jesus is magnified, while in Leviticus, God states He will be glorified before all people. This connection highlights the theme of God''s holiness and the reverence it inspires.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 19, 18, 45, 10, 10, 10, 'confessed, and shewed their deeds', 'Connection of Confession and Belief', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of confession in the process of faith. Acts 19:18 highlights the act of confessing deeds, while Romans 10:10 states that confession is integral to salvation.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 19, 18, 19, 32, 5, 5, 'confessed', 'Confession of Sin', 'Both passages emphasize the act of confession. Acts 19:18 mentions believers confessing their deeds, while Psalms 32:5 speaks of acknowledging and confessing transgressions to the Lord.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 19, 18, 40, 3, 6, 6, 'confessed', 'Confession and Baptism Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the act of confession related to faith and repentance. In Acts, believers confess their deeds, while in Matthew, individuals confess their sins before baptism.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 19, 18, 3, 16, 21, 21, 'confessed, and shewed their deeds', 'Confession of Sins Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the act of confession regarding sins. In Acts, believers confess their deeds, while in Leviticus, Aaron confesses the iniquities of Israel over the goat. This connection highlights the communal aspect of acknowledging wrongdoing.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 19, 18, 3, 26, 40, 40, 'confessed, and shewed their deeds', 'Confession of Iniquity', 'Both passages emphasize the act of confession regarding wrongdoing. Acts 19:18 highlights believers confessing their deeds, while Leviticus 26:40 speaks of confessing iniquity. This connection highlights the importance of acknowledging one''s sins.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 19, 18, 18, 33, 27, 28, 'confessed, and shewed their deeds', 'Confession and Deliverance', 'Both passages emphasize the act of confession as a means of deliverance. In Acts, believers confess their deeds, while in Job, acknowledging sin leads to salvation from the pit.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 19, 18, 20, 28, 13, 13, 'confessed', 'Confession and Forgiveness Theme', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of confession for receiving mercy. Acts 19:18 highlights believers confessing their deeds, while Proverbs 28:13 states that confessing and forsaking sins leads to mercy.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 19, 19, 44, 13, 8, 8, 'curious arts', 'Connection of Sorcery and Faith', 'Both passages emphasize the conflict between faith and sorcery. In Acts 19:19, the burning of books related to ''curious arts'' signifies a rejection of such practices, while Acts 13:8 shows Elymas the sorcerer opposing the faith.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 19, 19, 1, 35, 4, 4, NULL, 'Rejection of Idolatry', 'Both passages emphasize the act of rejecting and destroying objects associated with idolatry. In Acts, the burning of books represents a public renunciation of curious arts, while in Genesis, the giving of strange gods to Jacob signifies a turning away from idols.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 19, 19, 2, 32, 20, 20, 'burned them before all men', 'Destruction of Idolatrous Practices', 'This connection highlights the act of burning as a means of rejecting idolatry. Both passages emphasize the destruction of objects associated with false worship.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 19, 19, 5, 7, 25, 26, 'burned them before all men', 'Burning of Abominable Items', 'This connection highlights the act of burning items associated with idolatry and the rejection of abominations. Both passages emphasize the importance of destroying objects that are considered cursed or an abomination to God.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 19, 19, 23, 2, 20, 21, NULL, 'Idolatry and Repentance', 'This connection highlights the act of discarding idols, as seen in both passages. In Acts, the burning of books represents a rejection of false practices, paralleling Isaiah''s call to cast away idols of silver and gold.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
